## The Week at a Glance

- 🔴 **High — AI agents are an active attack surface.** Microsoft's security team has confirmed that AI tools using the Model Context Protocol (MCP) can be manipulated by attackers to steal data or take unauthorized actions. Any organization deploying AI agents should treat this as an open risk, not a future concern.
- 🔴 **High — Multiple newly published security vulnerabilities require patching review.** This week's update batch includes over a dozen CVEs touching network protocols, AI/ML frameworks, and cryptographic libraries. Organizations with cyber insurance, HIPAA, or CMMC obligations must confirm patch coverage with their IT teams promptly.
- 🟡 **Medium — Entra identity backup is now live and requires activation decisions.** Microsoft Entra Backup and Recovery reached general availability this week, giving organizations the ability to restore accidentally deleted or maliciously altered identity records. This capability requires Entra ID P1 or P2 licensing and should be reviewed for inclusion in your disaster recovery plan.
- 🟢 **Low — Advanced Intune device management tools are now included in M365 E3 and E5 licenses at no extra charge.** Capabilities that previously required a separate purchase are now bundled in, effective July 1. Your IT team should inventory which of these newly available tools address open endpoint risk items.

*Sources: [Microsoft Security Blog — MCP Security 2026](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/microsoft-security-community/the-state-of-mcp-security-in-2026/ba-p/4531327) · [Entra Backup and Recovery GA](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/microsoft-entra-blog/microsoft-entra-backup-and-recovery-is-now-generally-available/ba-p/4521997) · [Intune Suite in M365 E3/E5](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/microsoft-intune-blog/advanced-microsoft-intune-capabilities-now-available-in/ba-p/4529335)*

---

## Why This Week Matters

The expansion of AI agents from experimental tools into production workflows has outpaced the security controls most organizations have in place. Microsoft's own security researchers have now documented how AI agents can be weaponized through manipulated instructions to leak sensitive data or take unauthorized actions, and this risk exists in deployed environments today. At the same time, Microsoft is delivering meaningful defensive capabilities: the ability to recover an entire identity environment from a backup after an attack, and bundled endpoint controls that reduce standing privilege without additional licensing spend. The one thing leadership must understand this week is that AI deployment and AI security governance must move together; the gap between them is now measurable in terms of breach risk.

*Sources: [Microsoft Security Blog — Securing AI Agents](https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/security/blog/2026/06/30/securing-ai-agents-ai-tools-move-from-reading-acting/) · [What's New in Microsoft Security: June 2026](https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/security/blog/2026/06/30/whats-new-in-microsoft-security-june-2026/)*

